!! Wikitext EBNF Grammar

This tiddler presents an EBNF-like grammar for TiddlyWiki's wikitext syntax. The grammar is derived from the parser source code in `core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/` and its `rules/` subdirectory. It is not a formal specification but a practical reference that mirrors how the parser actually works.

The six companion tiddlers cover each grammar area in detail. This page provides the top-level document structure, explains the three rule types and key parsing concepts, and includes a quick-reference table of every parser rule.

!! Document Structure

A wikitext document is parsed in two phases. First, pragma lines at the top of the text are consumed. Then the remaining text is parsed as content.

```
Document        ::= PragmaBlock? ContentBlock
PragmaBlock     ::= ( Pragma Newline )*
ContentBlock    ::= ( Block | InlineRun | BlankLine )*
InlineRun       ::= ( Inline | PlainText )+
```

The `PragmaBlock` ends as soon as the parser encounters a line that does not match any pragma rule. From that point forward only block and inline rules are tried.

!! Rule Types

Every parser rule declares one or more //types// that control when it is eligible to match.

!!! Pragmas

Pragma rules are processed first, before any content is rendered. They configure the parsing environment: defining procedures and functions (`\procedure`, `\function`, `\widget`), importing variables (`\import`), controlling whitespace handling (`\whitespace trim`), selecting parser modes (`\parsermode`), and declaring parameters (`\parameters`).

Pragma lines always start at column 0. The pragma phase ends at the first non-pragma, non-blank line.

Example:

```
\whitespace trim
\procedure greeting(name)
Hello, <<name>>!
\end
```

!!! Block Rules

Block rules match at line-start positions and produce structural elements: headings (`!`), bullet and ordered lists (`*`, `#`), tables (`|`), code blocks (triple-backtick), quote blocks (`>`/`<<<`), horizontal rules (`---`), typed blocks (`$$`), style blocks (`@@`), and block-level widgets/transclusions.

Block content typically terminates at a double newline (`\n\n`), which signals the end of the current block and returns to the top-level content loop.

!!! Inline Rules

Inline rules match within text runs. They handle formatting (bold, italic, strikethrough, superscript, subscript, underscore), links (`[[link]]`, `[ext[url]]`, CamelCase wiki links, external URLs), inline transclusions and macro calls, images, HTML entities, code spans, hard line breaks, and inline widgets.

Inline runs terminate when the parser encounters a regex pattern set by the enclosing context -- for example, a closing `''` for bold, a `|` or `\n` in a table cell, or the end-of-input.

!! How the Parser Chooses Rules

Several concepts are central to understanding the parser:

* ''Position-based competition'' -- All eligible rules test their regex against the remaining text. The rule whose match starts closest to the current position wins. If two rules match at the same position, the first one registered wins.
* ''Block termination at double-newline'' -- A blank line (two consecutive newlines) ends most block constructs and returns control to the top-level content loop.
* ''Inline termination pattern'' -- Each inline-parsing context supplies a `terminatorRegExp`. The inline run ends when that pattern matches, giving control back to the enclosing block or widget.
* ''Recursive parsing'' -- Many rules parse their body recursively. A list item, for instance, parses its content as an inline run. A `<$list>` widget parses its body as a full content block. This recursive structure means the same inline rules apply everywhere text appears.

